\begin_layout Title
Status Consumption and Income Inequality
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
Status motivations for consumption have generated an immense interest at
 a time when social mobility has been relatively stagnant - but the consequences
 of inequality on consumption are still poorly understood.
 To explain status motivations under environments of income inequality,
 we treat opportunities for mobility as an explicit link between economic
 and social goals of the individual and focus on instances of status consumption
 where consumption can be viewed as an investment towards future economic
 success.
 The effect of relative incomes on the agentsâ€™ consumption and labour decisions
 is then explored in an economy with a dynamic hierarchy of rich and poor
 positions that participants are able to move between.
 Relying on diminishing returns to wealth utility - optimised by participants
 endowed with randomly distributed success-determining attributes - the
 results indicate that a rise in income inequality provides more incentive
 to participate in status competitions.
 As participants bear costs for the mobility, the equilibrium conditions
 suggest only two states in the long-run - one where both rich and poor
 strive for status and the other where only the rich participate in status
 competitions.
\end_layout

