\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
noindent
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Assuming EUT participants, consider the simpler case of binding constraint
 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{1}<\overline{\nu}<y_{2}$
\end_inset

 first .
 With the assumption of a stability in long-term participant behaviour (which
 itself is a result of observed probability of success), mixed-strategies
 are not considered relevant in the current set up.
 Considering pure strategies for participation, the rich participant would
 thus participate only when the utility from participating would be higher
 than from not participating i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $u(y_{2}-\overline{\nu})+\frac{p_{2}u(y_{2})+(1-p_{2})u(y_{1})}{\delta}>u(y_{2})+\frac{u(y_{2})+u(y_{1})}{2\delta}$
\end_inset

 .
 This results in the following condition
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\frac{(p_{2}-1/2)(u(y_{2})-u(y_{1}))}{\delta} & >u(y_{2})-u(y_{2}-\overline{\nu})
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With income differences being the same an increase in participation cost
 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\nu}$
\end_inset

 discourages participation since RHS increases with 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\nu}$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $\because u(y_{2}-\overline{\nu})$
\end_inset

 is decreasing in 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\nu}$
\end_inset

) and may fail the above condition.
 Similarly, with participation cost 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\nu}$
\end_inset

 being the same, an increase in income-difference 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{2}-y_{1}$
\end_inset

 is in the rich participant's interest whereas a narrowing of income differences
 reduces incentive for the participant to participate by possibly failing
 the above condition.
 All else being the same, higher impatience (lower time-discounted value
 of money or a higher 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

) would also discourage participation.
 Therefore, when budget is binding for the poor participant i.e.
 if the poor participant cannot participate due to 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{1}<\overline{\nu}$
\end_inset

, then narrower income differences, higher participation costs and higher
 patience for savings (common for both rich and poor participants) all encourage
 the rich participant to withdraw from the game.
 This also means that wider income differences (
\begin_inset Formula $y_{2}-y_{1}$
\end_inset

) combined with lower participation costs (
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\nu}$
\end_inset

) may together help maintain the equilibrium where only the rich participates.
 Similarly, wider income differences ( higher 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{2}-y_{1}$
\end_inset

 ) and more patience for savings (higher 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

) would together maintain the incentive for the rich participant to participate.
 These conclusions very much fit with the sociological observations made
 in the literature about status 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "HirschSocialLimits,GalbraithEssential"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Non-Binding-constraint"

\end_inset

Non-Binding constraint
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
noindent
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When budget is non-binding, then participation of the rich participant is
 her dominant strategy if the condition is also 
\begin_inset Formula $u(y_{2})+\frac{u(y_{2})p_{2}'+(1-p_{2}')u(y_{1})}{\delta}<u(y_{2}-\overline{\nu})+\frac{u(y_{2})+u(y_{1})}{2\delta})$
\end_inset

 i.e.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\frac{(1/2-p_{2}')(u(y_{2})-u(y_{1}))}{\delta} & >u(y_{2})-u(y_{2}-\overline{\nu})
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The inferences on how 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{2}-y_{1}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\nu}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

 influence the participation (see Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Binding-constraint"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) remain the same for the above condition.
 To discuss the more general Nash equilibria, consider the conditions for
 all of the Cases I, II, III and IV to become a Nash equilibrium.
 For ease of notation we define the following for a given 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\nu},y_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{2}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
U_{1} & \equiv u(y_{1})-u(y_{1}-\overline{\nu})
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
U_{2} & \equiv u(y_{2})-u(y_{2}-\overline{\nu})
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One could view 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{2}$
\end_inset

 as the immediate gain in wealth utility from withdrawing.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $u(\cdot)$
\end_inset

 represents a diminishing utility, then it is also necessary for 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{1}<y_{2}$
\end_inset

 that 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
U_{2} & <U_{1}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

