 where status is exclusive to the rich, the other long-term equilibrium
 is one where both rich and poor must strive for status.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The second detail highlighted by the model is the interplay of participation
 costs (threshold) and income-differences in status competitions.
 The model explains how a withdrawal from expenditures such as education
 could be the result of a combined effect of both participation costs and
 income-differences.
 More specifically, high participation costs push the equilibrium to one
 where only rich participate in status-related competitions while high income
 differences may continue to incentivise the poor to participate.
